According to the trade agreement ancillary arrangement announced Monday , the new US trade agreement @ - @ Mexico @ - will retain US President Donald Trump &apos;s ability to implement a 25 % tariff threat on imported cars , while substantially exempting passenger cars , pickups , and car parts imported from Canada and Mexico from tariffs .
If Trump imposes so @-@ called drops of 232 on cars for national @-@ security reasons , both Mexico and Canada will have 2.6 million taxable passenger cars exported annually to the US .
Under the ancillary arrangements , pickups produced in both countries would be granted full tariff exemptions .
If Trump imposes tariffs on cars , Mexico will receive $ 108 billion a year in tax exemptions for automobile parts , and Canada will receive $ 32.4 billion .
Both quotas are well above current production levels in both countries and provide scope for export growth in both countries .
