According to foreign media reports , in a nursery centre on the outskirts of the capital of South Africa , Pretoria , it is hard to see any anomalies in the two little lion playing together , but none of them are .
The University of Pretoria announced that it was the first child ever born in artificial fertilization -- the first pair in the world .
In @-@ school scientists are working to study the reproductive system of the mother African lion .
Ganswin , Director of the Mammalian Institute at the University of Pretoria , said that the two young lion , born on 25 August , were very healthy and normal .
After 18 months of intensive experimentation , his team was able to reach this breakthrough .
Ganswin said in an interview with the media : &quot; We collected sperm from a healthy lion . &quot;
Then , when the hormone content in the mother &apos;s lion reaches the appropriate level , the researcher gives it artificial fertilization .
Ganswin said : Fortunately , the results were successful .
He said that the researchers had tried several times , but surprisingly so little effort had been spent .
e said that the aforementioned research breakthroughs can be verified repeatedly , and scientists hope that this technology can be used to rescue large cats on the verge of extinction .
The International Union for Conservation of Nature ( IUCN ) noted that the Lions had been eradicated in 26 countries in Africa and that the total number of surviving wild Lions had fallen sharply by 43 per cent over the past 20 years , leaving only about 20,000 left .
African lion is classified by the organization as a endangered animal .
Ganswin said : If we don &apos;t do something for these animals , they will face extinction .
The new technology , he said , did not require that the lion be fed , but simply that the sperm be injected into a pregnant lion , as had been done in North America and Europe with regard to ring elephants .
