Ignoring the US threat !
EU may enter into a crude oil purchase agreement with Iran
The US government recently announced that it will resume a new round of sanctions against Iran in November , and even urged other countries to reduce their imports of Iranian oil .
America &apos;s allies , however , do not seem to have heard .
According to a report by the New York Times of the United States , Iranian Foreign Minister Zarif revealed during his visit on the 29th that despite the threat by the United States to sanction any country doing business with Iran , Tehran is approaching an agreement with the EU on the sale of crude oil .
At the heart of the agreement is an attempt to establish a new payment mechanism to replace dollar transactions with barter or local @-@ currency denomination .
The approach was intended to bypass the United States and prevent it from impeding financial transfers .
At the same time , while the EU is working to broker the agreement , some French and British officials are worried that , if it materializes , it would be the most open confrontation between the EU and the US that opposes America &apos;s withdrawal from the Iran nuclear deal .
According to the US media , Zarif &apos;s words sounded more optimistic than in recent months in an hour @-@ long interview .
Because the agreement has the ability to squeeze America &apos;s traditional allies , it has effectively thwarted US attempts to cut Iranian revenues .
This would ensure that we sell our oil and benefit from it , and Zarif believes that , under the 2015 agreement , countries have a legitimate right to trade with Iran .
The EU &apos;s foreign policy chief , Federika Mogherini , also said a few days ago that no sovereign country or organization can accept others to decide with whom it can trade .
She also predicted , however , that prior to the next sanctions imposed by the United States Government in November , it would be possible for United States leaders to adopt a range of financial instruments aimed at targeting banks , businessmen and countries that had commercial dealings with Tehran .
Last May , the US government unilaterally announced its withdrawal from the Iran nuclear deal on the grounds that it was flawed , arguing that it would not permanently ban Iran &apos;s production of nuclear fuel .
The US then threatened to ban companies that buy Iranian oil and other commodities from doing business in the US .
This threat caused some companies to leave Tehran and the Iranian currency plummeted .
Companies like Airbus and the French oil giant Daudard have cancelled billions of dollars in investment in Iraq .
British and French officials have said that the US government may take the upper hand .
Otherwise , according to a recent Turkish media report , US sanctions do not seem to have had a significant impact on Iran &apos;s oil exports .
Iran &apos;s oil minister , Zangane , recently revealed that no country except South Korea has stopped buying Iranian oil .
Both Zarif and Iranian President Hassan Rouhani believe that the US has committed a series of acts aimed at seducing Iran into violating the agreement .
Zarif also dismissed a series of verbal attacks on the US side , and when asked whether the US would overthrow the current Iranian government with ever @-@ increasing fiscal pressure , Zarif even laughed that it was a strategy of regime change , which was the real goal of the US .
