Upon the signature and approval of Premier Li Keqiang , the State Council recently issued the Decision on Further Reduction of the Industrial Products Production Licensing Catalogue and Simplified Approval Procedure .
The Decision provides for further reduction of the industrial product production license management catalogue , elimination of 14 industrial product production license management , and delegation of authority for 4 industrial product production license management to the provincial people &apos;s governments quality technical supervision department .
As a result of this reform , the number of products subject to industrial product production licensing will be reduced from 38 last year to the current 24 .
The Decision clarifies that the product in the catalogue is subject to a simplified approval process .
The first is to change the pre @-@ licensing product inspection organized by the licensing authority to a product inspection qualification report issued by a qualified inspection inspection inspection agency submitted by the enterprise at the time of application .
Second , in addition to hazardous chemicals , the quality technical supervision department of the provincial people &apos;s government ( the market supervision authority ) carries out a back @-@ up on @-@ site inspection of products that are licensed . Once the enterprise submits a qualified application and product inspection report and makes a commitment to ensuring product quality safety , it can obtain a production license after a formal review of the qualification , and then undergo a on @-@ site review within a specified time frame .
Third , when enterprises produce different categories of products in their catalogues , in accordance with the &quot; one size fits all &quot; principle , when applying for a new license or when applying for a new license , they review and issue a license .
The Decision calls on all regions and relevant departments to move forward with the process of reducing the catalogue and simplifying the approval process .
Enhance the publicity and back @-@ up on @-@ site review of enterprises &apos; commitments , strengthen credit supervision and restraint measures , implement corporate quality corporate responsibility , and cancel production licenses for false commitments and non @-@ conforming requirements .
For products that are not licensed to produce industrial products , ex post facto supervision needs to be effectively strengthened . Products related to public health and safety , environmental protection , etc . , can be converted to mandatory certification , positive lists are drawn up and made public to society , certification standards are harmonized , and the cost of mandatory certification is in principle covered by the financial system at all levels .
Support measures to encourage voluntary certification and promote branding and market expansion .
Advanced international standards for marking should be promoted to improve the quality of industrial products .
Fully utilize the role of third @-@ party social organizations to ensure the safety of the quality of industrial products .
For products that retain production licensing for industrial products , we need to improve the standard system , exploit the industry &apos;s regulatory advantages , strengthen whoever approves them , who supervises their responsibilities , dynamically assess product quality safety risks , and , where appropriate , reduce cataloguing , decentralize approval authority or convert them into certification management .
In September , China &apos;s Integrated PMI Ring @-@ Up Manufacturing PMI Ring @-@ up fell .
According to data released by the National Bureau of Statistics on the 30th , in September , China &apos;s composite PMI output index was 54.1 % , which is higher than the previous month &apos;s and annual averages of 0.3 and 0.1 percentage points , indicating that Chinese enterprises &apos; production and business activities remained generally stable .
In that month , the index of manufacturing production and the index of non @-@ manufacturing business activity , which constituted the composite PMI output index , were 53.0 per cent and 54.9 per cent , respectively , a drop of 1 per cent .
Of these , China &apos;s manufacturing PMI is 50.8 % , and the ring @-@ to @-@ ring ratio has fallen by 0.5 percentage points .
Zhao Qinghai said that the manufacturing PMI this month has five main characteristics :
One is that the fundamentals of manufacturing are generally stable .
Of the 21 industries surveyed , 14 have PMIs in expansion zones , with manufacturing PMIs , such as pharmaceuticals , specialized equipment and electrical and mechanical equipment , located above 53.5 per cent at higher operational levels and growing faster .
The second is a small fluctuation in supply and demand .
The production index and the new order index were 53.0 per cent and 52.0 per cent , respectively , falling 0.3 and 0.2 percentage points from the previous month , while supply and demand remained in a steady but slightly slower expansion .
The index of new export orders and the index of imports were 48.0 per cent and 48.5 per cent , respectively , lower than the 1.4 and 0.6 percentage points of the previous month , respectively , and both reached low levels during the year .
Fourth , the cost of purchasing raw materials for enterprises has increased .
The price index for the purchase of major raw materials was 59.8 per cent , up 1.1 percentage points from the previous month , and the factory price index was 54.3 per cent , the same as the previous month , all at the peak of the year .
Fifth , large enterprises are functioning robustly and the performance of small businesses continues to improve .
The largest company , PMI , with 52.1 % , has been in the expansion range of 52.0 % and above since last month , and this month &apos;s production index and the new order index have both risen , which is the main driver of manufacturing expansion ; medium @-@ sized enterprises , with 48.7 % , down from 1.7 percentage points in the previous month , are in the contraction zone ; and small @-@ scale enterprises , with 50.4 % , up from 0.4 percentage points in the previous month , have risen for two consecutive months .
In the same month , the index of non @-@ manufacturing business activity in China was 54.9 per cent , up 0.7 percentage points from the previous month , and recovered for two consecutive months .
Zhao Qinghai believes that non @-@ manufacturing industries generally continue to maintain a steady and positive trend .
Indicators of business activity in such industries as road transport , securities and real estate continued to fall below critical points and overall business volume decreased .
Reuters Nagoya , November 5 - Bank of Japan Governor Haruhiko Kuroda said on Monday that the Bank recognizes that prolonged ultra @-@ loose monetary policy can squeeze financial institutions &quot; profitability and potentially destabilize the country &apos;s banking system .
But , given low inflation and uncertainty in the overseas economies , he said , the Bank of Japan needed to maintain its massive stimulus package , while paying close attention to the pros and cons of its policies .
The Bank of Japan fully acknowledged that the strength of financial institutions would be increasingly affected by continued monetary easing , and Haruhiko Kuroda said in his speech to business leaders in Nagoya .
He said that the banking system could become unstable in the event of a serious negative shock if financial institutions were to take risks more aggressively to compensate for the narrowing of profit margins over the years as a result of low interest rates .
Though these risks are not significant at the moment , the central bank will follow developments closely , encouraging financial institutions to take the necessary steps , as he put it .
The minutes of the BOJ meeting , published earlier Monday , show that the BOJ &apos;s Policy Committee discussed the rising costs of long @-@ term easing at its September interest @-@ rate meeting .
The minutes show that , according to one member , if the economy continues to expand , the BOJ will have more room for policy flexibility in the future .
The minutes of the meeting indicate that another member said that the Committee should discuss how long the Bank of Japan could maintain the stimulus policy , given its limitations over the course of the policy .
Haruhiko Kuroda said that the Bank of Japan would assess the financial risks posed by easing , while also considering the uncertainty surrounding Japan &apos;s economic prospects , which could affect global demand as a result of trade friction between China and the US and growing protectionism .
The impact of such problems on Japan &apos;s economy is limited for the time being , according to Haruhiko Kuroda .
He added that the impact on the Japanese economy could become greater if the problem persisted .
Strong monetary easing needs to be sustained , considering both positive and negative effects in a balanced manner , according to Haruhiko Kuroda .
Despite the increased downsides of radical stimulus packages , such as long @-@ term low interest rates that erode financial institutions &quot; profitability , low inflation has forced the Bank of Japan to maintain it .
The BOJ maintained monetary policy last month ; in the face of the risks posed by the end of the global trade war , Haruhiko Kuroda ruled out a near @-@ term interest @-@ rate hike .
Corporate identity on Tesla electric vehicle , Cardiff , United States , June 1 , 2018 .
Under a settlement agreement , Tesla cars in the United States and its executive director , Musk , have agreed to pay $ 20 million in fines to financial regulators , and Musk will resign from his position as chairman of the company , but remain CEO .
The settlement agreement will put an end to Tesla &apos;s two @-@ month @-@ long turmoil .
The securities fraud allegation settlement agreement disclosed by the United States Securities and Exchange Commission on Saturday would be a relief to investors .
Investors originally feared that a protracted legal battle would only hit the still @-@ losing electric car company further .
SEC indicted Musk for fraud on Thursday , arguing that its August 7 tweets mislead investors .
By extension , he is considering privatizing Tesla for $ 420 per share and has secured financing .
SEC asserts that these tweets are actually groundless and that the resulting market turmoil harms investors .
Investors and corporate @-@ governance experts claim that the agreement could strengthen Tesla , who has been hard hit by Musk &apos;s recent behavior .
Steven Heim , the head of Boston Common &apos;s asset management , said that the settlement should have subjected Musk to more scrutiny , while failing to take the devastating measures to drive him out of Tesla .
The asset management firm holds Panasonic shares in Tesla &apos;s battery manufacturer .
Under the proposed agreement , Tesla would have to appoint an independent chairman , two independent directors , and a board of directors to develop controls over Musk &apos;s external communications .
It is in the best interests of our markets and our investors , including Tesla shareholders , that the matter be resolved promptly and on the agreed terms , as President Cleton said in a statement .
The charges on Thursday led to the evaporation of about $ 7 billion in the market value of Tesla , which stood at $ 45.2 billion on Friday , down from $ 47.5 billion for General Motors .
In the settlement agreement , the SEC withdrew the demand to drive Musk out of the company .
Many investors claim that the penalty will be disastrous .
I believe that this is the best possible outcome for all those involved , Ivan Feinseth of the Tigron Financial Partners said Feinseth gave Teslamento a neutral grade and said that the SEC &apos;s punishment was a light penalty for Musk .
It is important for Tesla that he remain CEO .
Neither Musk nor Tesla acknowledged or denied the SEC &apos;s allegations in the settlement agreement , nor did they immediately respond to the request for comments .
The settlement agreement is still subject to court approval .
