TOKYO , October 1 - The quarterly short @-@ sighted survey released by the Bank of Japan on Monday shows that the confidence of large Japanese manufacturers reached its lowest level in more than a year during the September season , owing to rising costs of raw materials and a series of natural disasters affecting production , which put pressure on businesses .
The survey showed little evidence that rising global trade frictions had eroded the confidence of large manufacturers .
But the risk of a full @-@ blown trade war undermines firms &quot; business prospects and could threaten their capital spending .
Dynamic capital spending is a bright spot in Japan &apos;s economy .
The survey called into question the Bank of Japan &apos;s view that robust economic expansion would help push inflation toward the 2 % target , despite indications that firms were gradually shifting costs to customers .
amid worries over the global trade war , due to a slowdown in exports and weak factory production , the confidence of manufacturers has stalled , and Nanwuzhi , the chief researcher at the Golden Gold @-@ Gold @-@ Gold Institute in the agriculture industry , said .
Confidence remains high , and , because business profits are improving and prices are rising , I do not believe that confidence will continue to decline .
The short @-@ sighted survey showed that the large manufacturing performance index fell to a positive 19 in September from a positive 21 three months ago , a third consecutive quarter .
The market &apos;s estimated median value is positive 22 .
In September , the large non @-@ manufacturing outlook index declined from positive 24 surveyed in June to positive 22 , the first deterioration in eight quarters .
The Reuters Survey is positive 22 .
The survey showed that the outlook index remained stable in both large manufacturing and non @-@ manufacturing sectors in December .
Investors are not concerned about the decline in short @-@ sighted business prospects , with the Japanese stock daily index ... N225 climbing to a 27 @-@ year high on Monday , helping to improve Japanese firms &quot; export earnings prospects because of the continued depreciation of the Japanese yen .
Capital expenditures are robust .
Despite the decline in business confidence , recent short @-@ sightedness highlights the robustness of corporate capital spending programs , benefiting from renewed capacity and increased investment in robots and automation to cope with labor shortages as a result of aging populations .
The central bank &apos;s short @-@ sighted survey shows that large corporations plan to increase capital spending by 13.4 % for the fiscal year ending March 2019 .
At 13.6 per cent in the previous short @-@ sighted survey .
nan Wuzhi said that all enterprise capital spending plans for this fiscal year have grown by 8.5 % , close to the pace of Japan &apos;s bubble economy .
He said that there was room for further growth in capital spending , given the current profit forecast for small businesses , but much depended on the impact of the trade war on business confidence .
The short @-@ sighted survey showed an increase in the ability of firms to pass on costs , with large enterprise output price indices of positive 7 , the highest in a decade , an encouraging sign of progress in Japan &apos;s efforts to combat deflation .
The index measuring employment in large enterprises touches negative 23 , the most tight level since 1992 , highlighting the tightening of the job market .
Thanks to strong corporate spending , the Japanese economy rebounded in the second quarter of this year from the contraction of 1 @ - @ in March .
But the prospect of an export @-@ dependent Japanese economy is overshadowed by escalating trade frictions and disruptions to the supply chain in the summer .
