Foreign media : framework agreement between the United States and Canada on NAFTA .
# 91 ; Summary # 93 ; The agreement includes the opening of Canada &apos;s dairy market to the United States and the temporary non @-@ imposition by the United States of tariffs on cars produced in Canada .
According to foreign media reports , a Canadian source revealed on the evening of September 30 that the United States and Canada had reached a framework agreement on the North American Free Trade Agreement .
It was revealed that the agreement included the opening of Canada &apos;s dairy industry market to the United States and the temporary non @-@ imposition by the United States of tariffs on cars produced in Canada .
Last month , the United States and Mexico announced a preliminary agreement in principle on updating the North American Free Trade Agreement , but the United States and Canada failed to reach an agreement by the 31 August deadline set by the United States to extend the negotiations until 30 September .
Earlier , Canada &apos;s Foreign Minister , Ferrand &apos;s spokesman , said that Canada would sign only favorable agreements , focusing on substance rather than timetable , and that we would continue consultations in the hope of reaching agreements that would serve Canada &apos;s national interests .
More than 90 % of Brazilian women voters said that presidential candidates did not take women &apos;s needs into account .
According to the South American Expatriate Network , data published recently by the Brazilian National Institute of Geography ( IBGE ) indicate that more than 90 per cent of Brazilian women do not believe that presidential candidates take women &apos;s needs into account .
According to the report , the number of women in Brazil had reached 107 million , and if women were brought together to form a country , that country would rank 13th in the world , twice as many people as Spain .
In Brazil , women account for 52 per cent of the electorate and men for 48 per cent , while women represent a very high percentage of the electorate , they represent only 10 per cent of the electorate in Brazil &apos;s Congress .
Of the 193 countries in the world , Brazil ranked 154th in political participation , higher than the Arab countries .
After more than 20 years of struggle for rights , Brazilian women have still not succeeded in gaining their rightful rights .
As the Brazilian sociologist Natalia Mori has pointed out , this phenomenon is due to the combination of ancient patriarchal society , racism , and capitalist values .
Politics is supposed to be a citizen &apos;s claim to citizenship , identity , access to public goods , and the formation of one society by several social groups , but Brazilian politics is a monopoly of one group , and the majority of the population is not represented .
A previous study by the Brazilian Machine Institute ( Locomotiva ) also noted that 94 per cent of Brazilian women do not feel that elected politicians represent their rights , 90 per cent disagree with the decisions taken by politicians and 93 per cent disagree with the current government policy .
We need to reverse the underrepresentation of women in parliament , with Brazil &apos;s political system still suffering from inequality , with so far serious gender , class , and racial discrimination in Brazilian politics , as Natalia Mori put it .
Despite women &apos;s lack of empowerment , most Brazilian women still believe in the power of democracy .
The survey showed that 76 per cent of women believed that they could make a difference in democratic elections and 72 per cent were interested in politics .
In addition , 55 per cent of women believe that democracy is the best way to make women less prejudiced .
