Reuters , November 5 - Hong Kong property prices fell back for two consecutive months after seeing the peak , Hong Kong Financial Authority President Chen Delin said on Monday that time is still needed to see if the housing market has entered a downward cycle , and if confirmed , consider relaxing the tightening of countercyclical measures in due course .
Chen Delin added that if property prices were to be adjusted back , those who would be the first to be affected would be those who set up their businesses at the peak of the housing market , but it was expected that there would be , for example , a sharp drop in property prices during the Asian financial storm in 1997 , and that citizens would have a much lower chance of selling property at significantly reduced prices .
Chen Delin led several senior officials of the Authority to attend the LegCo briefing and said that if they confirmed that the housing market was entering a downward cycle , they could gradually relax their measures when appropriate .
However , at present , only a few weeks of data are available . It is still too early to talk about relaxation . It will still take more time to see if the housing market is going into a downward cycle .
Since October 2009 , the Authority has launched eight rounds of counter @-@ cyclical measures to significantly tighten mortgages in various types of property , including reducing the number of mortgages and requiring mortgage applicants to pass rigorous stress tests to improve bank risk management and earthquake resistance .
As Hong Kong formally enters the interest @-@ rate hike cycle , the Hong Kong @-@ wide private housing price index for 8 @ - @ September has peaked for two consecutive months , with the monthly decline in September increasing to 1.44 per cent .
However , the cumulative increase in the first three quarters of the year was still 10.2 per cent .
According to the Hong Kong Monetary Authority , the financial health of households measuring Hong Kong &apos;s resilience to financial risks is still healthy . In the second quarter of this year , the proportion of households in Hong Kong without mortgages reached 66 per cent , up from an average of 60 per cent in 2009 @ - @ 11 ; the average number of new mortgages issued was 47 per cent and 34 per cent respectively , up from 64 per cent and 41 per cent in 2009 @ - @ 11 .
However , Chen Delin said that high earthquake resistance did not mean that residents of established businesses would not suffer downside damage , because property valuation would fall , and those who bought buildings during peak periods would bear the brunt of it .
Although the Authority has tightened bank lending to mortgage lenders , business owners can obtain high levels of mortgage lending , either through mortgage insurance or through the provision of mortgage loans by development agents .
Chen Delin said that , together with the mortgage loans provided to developers , the number of borrowers can now reach 85 @ - @ 90 % , and if property prices fall by 10 % , negative assets will emerge ( that is , the market value of the property industry falls below the level of the total outstanding mortgage loans ) .
However , Nguyen Guy Hsien , Vice President of the Kim Authority , pointed out that the authorities estimated that a high percentage of the total amount of mortgages provided by development agents represented only 2 @ - @ 2.5 per cent of the total amount of bank mortgages , which remained low .
At the peak of Hong Kong &apos;s negative assets in 2003 , the number of negative assets exceeded 100,000 , accounting for 22 per cent of the construction supply .
As of the third quarter of this year , Hong Kong recorded zero negative assets for seven consecutive quarters .
