Since the mid @-@ 2000s , Paul Thomas , a farmer in North Dakota , United States , has grown an increasing number of soybeans on his land as Chinese demand for oilseeds has grown .
This shift peaked this year , when he planted 1,600 acres of soybeans on 5,000 acres of land , a scale not seen before .
But Thomas and many farmers like him plan to convert by 2019 the staple food crops of former US agricultural areas : maize and wheat .
This year , American farmers cultivated more soybeans than maize , for the first time in 35 years .
Other food crops are planned because , against the backdrop of US President Donald Trump &apos;s trade war with China , American farmers face difficulties selling soybeans .
China usually buys about 60 % of the US exports of soybeans , but , as a result of the trade war , almost no American soybeans have been purchased in recent months , causing soybean prices to fall to a decade &apos;s low level .
Thomas intends to grow more wheat next year , hoping to earn more by reducing dependence on crops that depend on Chinese demand .
Thomas said that soybean prices have brought us a painful blow .
He said that without Chinese purchase , the spot price of soybeans near his farm was $ 7.10 per Putin , while the price necessary to cover the cost was $ 8.50 .
US farmers have a record area under soya cultivation this year , and the harvest is expected to reach a record high .
At such a time of vulnerability , they have been hit by trade wars .
In response to Trump &apos;s imposition of tariffs on imports of Chinese goods , China imposed import tariffs on imports of US soybeans in July .
The US Department of Agriculture will issue its first forecast report on next year &apos;s cultivated area , which will include consideration of the impact of tariffs .
The projection is expected to confirm the expectation of a decrease in soybean seeding by civil society institutions .
According to a report that Reuters saw , on October 19 , Informa Economics projected an increase in maize cultivation of 4 % to 92.7 million acres ( 37.5 million hectares ) in 2019 and a reduction in soybean cultivation of 7 % to 83 million acres .
Informa also projects a 4 per cent increase in wheat cultivation in the United States .
The area of soybeans planted before retaliatory tariffs were imposed rose to 89.6 million acres this year , about 15 million acres higher than a decade ago .
The area under maize cultivation has increased by less than 5 million acres since 2008 to 89.1 million acres , and this year wheat cultivation stands at 47.8 million acres , the lowest level in 100 years .
Aron Carlson , President of the Illinois Corn Planting Association , has 3,600 acres of cultivated land , almost half of which this year is devoted to soybeans , but plans to cut it in the future .
He said that it was possible to increase maize cultivation by up to 20 per cent on his farm in northern Illinois , the largest soybean growing state in the United States .
Soybeans produce lower yields per acre than maize , but require less fertilizer , making soybeans generally less expensive to grow .
If farmers move to final maize , costs may increase , but some enterprises , including Andersons Inc . , will benefit .
Executive Director Andersons Pat Bowe said to Reuters that he expected the conversion of maize to fertilizer use .
Bayer is also expected to benefit from the conversion of farmers to maize .
